						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So an image rendered by a NES where ALL the palettes are the same hue (from the same "column" of the palette), no dot crawl or artifacts appear, right ?</div><br />$0x and $3x are less saturated (sinusoid with smaller amplitude) than $1x and $2x. The artifacts from this are very subtle.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Also because the NES uses square wave instead of sine wave for the color-burst, this makes even more harmonics appear.</div>
<br />TVs that I've used appear to have a low-pass filter on their analog inputs to block details that are way out of the SDTV nominal bandwidth. An Apple IIe in 80-column text mode, for example, looks a lot sharper through an AppleColor Composite Monitor IIe than through a television (where 80-column text is nearly unreadable).</div>

